Research responsive design validation methodology — how to programmatically verify that a web page renders correctly across the full spectrum of device sizes, orientations, and input modalities. I am building a responsive design checker that uses Playwright to capture layouts at multiple viewport widths and a layout validator for CSS analysis.

Cover the standard breakpoint conventions: the Bootstrap/Tailwind breakpoint systems versus custom breakpoint strategies, and whether there is empirical evidence for which breakpoints matter most based on real-world device usage distributions (Statcounter, DeviceAtlas data). Has the proliferation of device sizes made the concept of discrete breakpoints obsolete in favor of truly fluid layout systems?

Research the specific responsive design failure modes that are most common and detectable programmatically: horizontal scrollbars introduced at narrow viewports (caused by fixed-width elements, non-responsive images without max-width: 100%, absolute positioned elements), text overflow (content clipped, overflowing containers, z-index-clipped text), touch target size violations (WCAG 2.2 success criterion 2.5.8 requires 24x24 CSS pixel minimum — how do you measure touch targets programmatically?), font scaling issues (text too small at mobile viewports, text that doesn't scale with user font size preferences), and viewport meta tag misconfigurations (user-scalable=no violates WCAG 1.4.4).

Cover CSS-specific analysis techniques: how do you detect potential responsive failures by analyzing CSS without rendering the page? Can static CSS analysis identify rules that will cause horizontal overflow at specific viewport widths? What is the relationship between CSS media query coverage and responsive completeness?

Research existing responsive testing frameworks: Galen Framework, Playwright's viewport manipulation, BrowserStack's responsive testing tools. What are the limits of viewport-only simulation versus real device testing?
